Abstract

This dissertation develops a rigorous mathematical framework for representing, updating, and stabilizing knowledge in artificial general intelligence (AGI) systems, grounded in the conservation laws of physics. The Fractal Knowledge Capsule (FKC) framework models knowledge as a tuple of semantic propositions, probabilistic confidences, and Noether-anchored invariants evolving on a Riemannian knowledge manifold M. Version 5 completes the architecture by bridging discrete capsule structures with continuous geometry through three interlocking extensions:

1. Sheaf-Theoretic Consistency: The FKC is defined as a sheaf \mathcal{F} over M, with Noether-anchored propositions forming a constant subsheaf. This guarantees that conservation laws are global sections, enforcing consistency across overlapping domains. Čech cohomology \check{H}^1(M,\mathcal{F}) provides a topological diagnostic for scientific paradoxes, and the Paradox Set \mathcal{P}\subset M localizes where local sections fail to glue.
2. Inverse Noether Problem: An inductive update operator T_{\text{up}} minimizes a symmetry-mismatch functional \mathcal{J}(L) on the space of Lagrangians \mathcal{L}, using the Helmholtz conditions as a filter to promote empirical invariants to exact Noether charges. The Helmholtz residual quantifies non‑variationality, allowing the system to label propositions as emergent or non‑physical.
3. Stochastic Stability: Knowledge evolution is modeled as an Itô stochastic differential equation on M. A Lyapunov function argument yields the Stochastic Sufficiency Bound with explicit Ricci curvature corrections. The Epistemic Heat Q_\infty obeys a Second Law of Epistemics, linking residual uncertainty to the entropy of evidence.

The complete update operator T = T_{\text{down}} \oplus T_{\text{up}} defines a Stochastic Variational Flow on a Riemannian Sheaf (SVFRS) — provably stable under noise, inductively complete, and globally consistent. The framework provides a computable test for distinguishing physical from emergent propositions via the Symmetry Gap \inf_{L\in\mathcal{L}} \mathcal{J}(L) > 0. All theorems from prior versions are preserved and strengthened.


Chapter 1: Introduction

1.1 Motivation: The Problem of Grounded AGI

Artificial intelligence systems have achieved remarkable performance in pattern recognition, language modeling, and game playing, yet they remain vulnerable to hallucination, logical inconsistency, and catastrophic forgetting. These failures stem from a common root: lack of grounding in invariant structures of the world. A system that learns correlations from data alone cannot distinguish between genuine causal laws and spurious statistical regularities.

Physics offers a solution: the conservation laws derived from symmetries via Noether's theorem provide an invariant core that any intelligent system should respect. This dissertation proposes that an AGI's knowledge base should be organized around Noether-anchored propositions — statements whose certainty is enforced by the underlying Lagrangian of the domain.

1.2 Overview of the Fractal Knowledge Capsule Framework

The FKC framework, introduced in Versions 1–4, models knowledge as a collection of capsules — tuples (S, R, P, T) where:

· S is a set of propositions,
· R is an entanglement graph (mutual information dependencies),
· P is a probability distribution over S (Bayesian confidence),
· T is a local update operator.

The knowledge manifold M is the space of all such capsules, metrized by the variation of information distance d_2. Version 4 proved that under a Noether coverage condition (sufficient fraction of propositions anchored to conservation laws), the AGI fixed point M^* exists uniquely and is globally attractive via Banach contraction.

Version 5 extends this to handle:

