Chapter 2: Mathematical Preliminaries

2.1 Riemannian Geometry and the Knowledge Manifold

Definition 2.1 (Knowledge Manifold). Let U = U_0/{\sim} be the quotient space of propositions under equivalence of probability distributions (see Section 2.3). A knowledge state is a probability measure \mu on U with finite second moment. The knowledge manifold M is the set of all such measures, equipped with a Riemannian metric derived from the Fisher information metric (or, more conveniently, the variation of information metric).

Theorem 2.1 (d₂ Metric Completeness). The variation of information distance

d_2(\mu,\nu) = \sqrt{ H(\mu|\nu) + H(\nu|\mu) }
\]  

where H(\cdot|\cdot) is conditional entropy, defines a complete metric on the probability simplex \Delta. Moreover, (\Delta, d_2) is compact.

Proof. See Versions 1–4; compactness follows from finite-dimensional simplex and continuity of d_2. ∎

Definition 2.2 (Sectional and Ricci Curvature). For a Riemannian manifold (M,g), the sectional curvature K(\Pi) at a point p for a plane \Pi \subset T_pM measures geodesic dispersion. The Ricci curvature \operatorname{Ric}(v,v) is the trace of the sectional curvature over planes containing v. In knowledge space, negative curvature indicates sensitivity to initial conditions (butterfly effect), positive curvature indicates clustering.

2.2 Noether's Theorem (Classical)

Theorem 2.2 (Noether, 1918). Let L(q,\dot{q},t) be a Lagrangian with action S = \int L\,dt. If L is invariant under a one-parameter family of transformations q \mapsto q + \epsilon X(q,\dot{q},t) (up to a total time derivative), then the quantity

J = \frac{\partial L}{\partial \dot{q}^i} X^i
\]  

is conserved along solutions of the Euler-Lagrange equations: \dot{J} = 0.

Off-shell identity:

\frac{d}{dt}\left(\frac{\partial L}{\partial \dot{q}^i}X^i\right) = \left(\frac{\partial L}{\partial q^i} - \frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial L}{\partial \dot{q}^i}\right) X^i .
\]  

Thus conservation holds when the Euler-Lagrange equations are satisfied.

2.3 Probability Metrics and Information Geometry

Definition 2.3 (Prokhorov Metric). For probability measures \mu,\nu on a Polish space,

\rho(\mu,\nu) = \inf\{\epsilon>0 : \mu(A) \le \nu(A^\epsilon)+\epsilon \text{ for all Borel } A\},
\]  

where A^\epsilon = \{x : d(x,A)<\epsilon\}. Prokhorov's theorem states that \rho metrizes weak convergence, and the space of probability measures is compact iff the underlying space is compact.

2.4 Sheaf Theory (Basic Concepts)

Definition 2.4 (Presheaf and Sheaf). Let (X,\tau) be a topological space. A presheaf \mathcal{F} of sets (or rings, etc.) assigns to each open set U\subset X a set \mathcal{F}(U) and to each inclusion V\subseteq U a restriction map \operatorname{res}_{U,V}:\mathcal{F}(U)\to\mathcal{F}(V) satisfying:

· \operatorname{res}_{U,U} = \operatorname{id},
· \operatorname{res}_{V,W}\circ\operatorname{res}_{U,V} = \operatorname{res}_{U,W} for W\subseteq V\subseteq U.

A presheaf is a sheaf if it additionally satisfies:

· Locality: If U = \bigcup_i U_i and s,t\in\mathcal{F}(U) with \operatorname{res}_{U,U_i}(s)=\operatorname{res}_{U,U_i}(t) for all i, then s=t.
· Gluing: If \{s_i\in\mathcal{F}(U_i)\} satisfy \operatorname{res}_{U_i,U_i\cap U_j}(s_i)=\operatorname{res}_{U_j,U_i\cap U_j}(s_j) for all i,j, then there exists s\in\mathcal{F}(\bigcup_i U_i) with \operatorname{res}_{\bigcup U_i,U_i}(s)=s_i for all i.

Definition 2.5 (Constant Sheaf). A sheaf \mathcal{F} is constant if for every nonempty open U, \mathcal{F}(U) is isomorphic to a fixed set A, and all restriction maps are the identity on A.

Definition 2.6 (Čech Cohomology). For an open cover \mathcal{U}=\{U_i\}, the Čech cohomology group \check{H}^1(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{F}) classifies obstructions to gluing local sections. Non-zero elements correspond to global inconsistencies.

2.5 Itô Calculus on Manifolds

Definition 2.7 (Itô SDE on a Riemannian Manifold). Let (M,g) be a Riemannian manifold. An Itô stochastic differential equation

dp_t = b(p_t)\,dt + \sigma(p_t)\,dW_t
\]  

is interpreted in a local chart using the Stratonovich-to-Itô correction involving the Levi-Civita connection. For a function V:M\to\mathbb{R}, Itô's lemma reads

dV(p_t) = \left( \nabla V \cdot b + \frac{1}{2} \operatorname{Tr}\left( \sigma^\mathsf{T} \operatorname{Hess} V \, \sigma \right) + \frac{1}{2} \operatorname{Ric}(\sigma,\sigma) \right) dt + (\nabla V)^\mathsf{T}\sigma \, dW_t,
\]  

where \operatorname{Ric}(\sigma,\sigma) = \sum_{i,j,k,l} \sigma^{ik} \sigma^{jl} R_{ijkl} and R is the Riemann curvature tensor (Elworthy, 1982). For flat manifolds, the curvature term vanishes.

