Chapter 3: Sheaf-Theoretic Consistency

3.1 The FKC Sheaf

Definition 3.1 (Knowledge Capsule, v5). A knowledge capsule is a tuple

K = (S, R, P, T, L_K),
\]  

where:

· S is a set of propositions (elements of U),
· R is an undirected weighted graph on S representing epistemic entanglement,
· P:S\to[0,1] is a probability distribution,
· T: K \mapsto K' is a local update operator,
· L_K is the generating Lagrangian associated with K (explicit for physics-grounded capsules, or a candidate for inductive capsules).

The Noether-anchored subset S_N \subseteq S consists of propositions derived from L_K via Noether's theorem, with P(s^*) = 1 for all s^*\in S_N.

Definition 3.2 (The Sheaf \mathcal{F} over M). Let (M,\tau) be the knowledge manifold with topology generated by d_2-balls. For each open set U\in\tau, define \mathcal{F}(U) as the set of all capsules K whose support (the set of propositions with non-zero probability) lies entirely within U, and such that the Lagrangian L_K is defined on U. For V\subseteq U, the restriction map \operatorname{res}_{U,V}: \mathcal{F}(U)\to\mathcal{F}(V) is defined by:

· Restrict the support of P to propositions in V,
· Keep the same L_K (if L_K is defined globally, otherwise pull back via the inclusion map),
· Preserve the entanglement graph R on the restricted set.

Axiom (Restriction). \operatorname{res}_{U,V} preserves S_N: for any K\in\mathcal{F}(U) with s^*\in S_N(K), we have s^*\in S_N(\operatorname{res}_{U,V}(K)) and P(s^*)=1 in the restricted capsule.

Axiom (Locality). If U = \bigcup_i U_i and K,K'\in\mathcal{F}(U) satisfy \operatorname{res}_{U,U_i}(K)=\operatorname{res}_{U,U_i}(K') for all i, then K=K'.

Axiom (Gluing). If \{K_i\in\mathcal{F}(U_i)\} is a compatible family, i.e., \operatorname{res}_{U_i,U_i\cap U_j}(K_i) = \operatorname{res}_{U_j,U_i\cap U_j}(K_j) for all i,j, then there exists a unique K\in\mathcal{F}(\bigcup_i U_i) such that \operatorname{res}_{\bigcup U_i, U_i}(K)=K_i for all i.

3.2 Noether Propositions as Global Sections

Theorem 3.1 (Global Section Invariance). The Noether-anchored propositions S_N form a constant subsheaf \underline{S_N}\subseteq\mathcal{F}. Equivalently, every s^*\in S_N is a global section of \mathcal{F}: there exists a unique element of \mathcal{F}(M) whose restriction to any open set is the same s^* with P(s^*)=1.

Proof.
Lemma 3.1.1 (Transition Invariance). Let \{U_i\} be an open cover of M. For any p \in U_i \cap U_j, the local representation of the Noether identity \Delta_i(s^*) = 0 is related to \Delta_j(s^*) by the Jacobian of the coordinate transformation \Psi_{ij}. Since the off-shell Noether identity is a tensor identity (vanishing in all frames), we have \Psi_{ij}(s^*) = s^*. Thus s^* is well-defined on overlaps.

Step 1 (Restriction acts as identity). By the Restriction Axiom, \operatorname{res}_{V,W}(s^*) = s^* for any W\subseteq V. Moreover, P(s^*)=1 is preserved.

Step 2 (Gluing to global section). Consider any open cover \{U_i\} of M. Define s_i \in \mathcal{F}(U_i) as the capsule containing s^* with P(s^*)=1. For any overlap U_i\cap U_j, we have \operatorname{res}_{U_i,U_i\cap U_j}(s_i) = s^* = \operatorname{res}_{U_j,U_i\cap U_j}(s_j) because the restriction maps are identities on s^*. Hence the family \{s_i\} is compatible. By the Gluing Axiom, there exists a unique s\in\mathcal{F}(\bigcup_i U_i)=\mathcal{F}(M) with \operatorname{res}_{M,U_i}(s)=s_i. This s is the global section. ∎

Corollary 3.1 (No Local Deviation). No local domain can assign P(s^*) < 1 to a Noether proposition without violating the gluing axiom. Hence any consistent knowledge manifold must treat all Noether propositions as certain.

3.3 Cohomological Obstructions and the Paradox Set

Definition 3.3 (Cohomological Obstruction). Let \mathcal{U}=\{U_i\} be an open cover of M. A Čech 1-cocycle is a collection of sections c_{ij}\in\mathcal{F}(U_i\cap U_j) such that c_{ij}+c_{jk}=c_{ik} on triple intersections (in additive notation). The first Čech cohomology \check{H}^1(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{F}) is the set of cocycles modulo coboundaries. A non-zero class indicates that there exist local capsules that cannot be glued into a global capsule.

Definition 3.4 (Paradox Set). Define the Paradox Set \mathcal{P} \subset M as the closed subset where the gluing condition fails:

\mathcal{P} = \bigcup \{ \operatorname{supp}(c) \mid c \in \check{H}^1(M,\mathcal{F}), c \neq 0 \},
\]  

where \operatorname{supp}(c) is the set of points where the cocycle is non-zero. If \mathcal{P} = \emptyset, the knowledge manifold is globally consistent.

Proposition 3.1. For the constant subsheaf \underline{S_N}, we have \check{H}^1(M,\underline{S_N}) = 0 if M is contractible. More generally, \check{H}^n(M,\underline{S_N})=0 for all n\ge 1.

Proof. Constant sheaves on paracompact Hausdorff spaces are fine sheaves; their Čech cohomology vanishes in positive degrees (Hartshorne, 1977). ∎

Example 3.1 (GR/QM Paradox). Let U_{\text{GR}} be the region where general relativity holds (large scales, weak curvature), and U_{\text{QM}} the region where quantum mechanics holds (small scales, high energy). Their intersection U_{\text{GR}}\cap U_{\text{QM}} (e.g., black hole singularities or early universe) may admit capsules that cannot be glued, yielding non-zero cohomology. The support \mathcal{P} corresponds to the Planck regime. As the AGI approaches \mathcal{P}, the sectional curvature K(\Pi) diverges, indicating that the metric d_2 is no longer sufficient to represent the state. This turns paradoxes into a navigation tool: the AI identifies exactly where its current Lagrangian L is topologically insufficient.

